00:04:50.260 --> 00:04:53.240
In the wise words of MC Hammer,
can't touch this.

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:02.620
So we've brought this up
many times in ADIA.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:05.130
And this is definitely a
recurring theme we see when

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:06.100
we're looking at apps.

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.320
So the first one is small
touch targets.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:12.170
So really, all touch targets
should be 48dp.

00:05:12.170 --> 00:05:15.200
We did write here that it could
go down to 38dp if you

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:16.170
absolutely need to.

00:05:16.170 --> 00:05:18.840
But really, 48dp is what you
should be aiming for.

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:19.290
Why?

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:23.090
Because that's sort of maps to
roughly nine millimeters, or I

00:05:23.090 --> 00:05:25.100
think somewhere between seven
and nine with a little bit of

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:26.180
variability.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:31.120
Which really ends up being the
perfect touch size for the

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:32.850
average person's fingers.

00:05:32.850 --> 00:05:36.220
So unless, I guess, you're
targeting a particular user

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:40.100
group with extremely small
hands, many babies, you should

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:42.310
really be shooting
for 48dp here.

00:05:42.310 --> 00:05:44.630
And then the second one-- and
this is something we see

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:47.960
frequently, all the time--
is no touch feedback.

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:50.660
And if you put an app in front
of any of us, you'll probably

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:52.610
see one of the first things
we do is we actually

00:05:52.610 --> 00:05:53.400
go and touch something.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:55.720
And then we slide our finger off
a little bit, just to see

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:57.950
if there's any touch
feedback there.

00:05:57.950 --> 00:06:00.570
So it's a pretty common mistake
to make, especially

00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:03.560
when you're not using the
standard button components.

00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:05.490
Because you may have to do a
little bit of extra work to

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:07.590
add that touch feedback.

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:09.950
But it really means that your
app feels much more

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:11.120
responsive.

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.510
ROMAN NURIK: And I think it's
also-- the no touch feedback,

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:15.900
as well as the previous
anti-pattern--

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:20.840
it really changes your app's
feeling of perceived latency.

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:23.960
When things don't respond, or
you can't do certain things,

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:26.000
there's an increased sense
of perceived latency.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.320
Or users perceive that
your app is slower

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:29.960
than it actually is.

00:06:29.960 --> 00:06:31.450
So it's one of the fastest--

00:06:31.450 --> 00:06:33.040
people talk about speed
all the time.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:34.760
Let's make our app faster,
faster, faster.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:36.050
It's not just about raw speed.

00:06:36.050 --> 00:06:38.140
It's really about
perceived speed.

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:39.075
ADAM KOCH: And the
funny thing is--

00:06:39.075 --> 00:06:41.190
go ahead, Nick.

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:42.310
NICK BUTCHER: Sorry, I was going
to say, I think it's

00:06:42.310 --> 00:06:43.320
really important when
[INAUDIBLE]

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:44.960
tools like digital interfaces.

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:47.810
Where the hottest style is all
about white space, and

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:49.230
[INAUDIBLE], and so on.

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:52.050
And it's really important to
communicate what is tappable.

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:53.880
What you can interact with.

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:55.670
And I think touch feedback is
