00:21:38.820 --> 00:21:43.240
So let's move to some of
the talking points.

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:44.690
So the first point.

00:21:44.690 --> 00:21:45.480
It's not genuine.

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:47.280
It's kind of like lying
to your users.

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:52.030
So it's not really the most
positive experience.

00:21:52.030 --> 00:21:54.290
Especially if you're taking
up a lot of the core

00:21:54.290 --> 00:21:56.860
UI with a web view.

00:21:56.860 --> 00:21:59.710
And following from that, the
performance is generally going

00:21:59.710 --> 00:22:01.000
to be degraded.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.930
If you have a drawer that's
built using a web view, you're

00:22:03.930 --> 00:22:05.450
going to notice that
it's not as smooth.

00:22:05.450 --> 00:22:06.510
It's not as responsive.

00:22:06.510 --> 00:22:09.990
It just doesn't behave like
the user would expect.

00:22:09.990 --> 00:22:13.070
And then from the example on
the previous page, don't

00:22:13.070 --> 00:22:17.110
package up a web app in an APK
just to be on Android.

00:22:17.110 --> 00:22:19.310
Just for the sake of being
in Google Play

00:22:19.310 --> 00:22:20.890
Store to be on Android.

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:22.060
We love web apps.

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:24.390
Web apps work great
on Android.

00:22:24.390 --> 00:22:26.720
But when the user expects
them is in the browser.

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:29.300
In the Chrome browser the system
browser, where they

00:22:29.300 --> 00:22:32.310
sort of understand that the
UI conventions and they're

00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:34.705
viewing a web page.

00:22:34.705 --> 00:22:35.930
NICK BUTCHER: And we're not
[INAUDIBLE] use WebViews at

00:22:35.930 --> 00:22:36.710
all, right?

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:38.360
There's several components
where it makes sense.

00:22:38.360 --> 00:22:42.840
Like Gmail, for example,
renders HTML and email.

00:22:42.840 --> 00:22:44.880
And it makes perfect sense to
use, say, on a web view

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:45.590
control there.

00:22:45.590 --> 00:22:48.200
Or if you're rendering some
news content, then perhaps

00:22:48.200 --> 00:22:49.300
that makes sense.

00:22:49.300 --> 00:22:50.800
I'm not saying don't
build your whole

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:51.880
application for this.

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:52.670
ADAM KOCH: Exactly, yeah.

00:22:52.670 --> 00:22:55.880
So another good example is
Pocket, which uses a WebView

00:22:55.880 --> 00:22:58.300
or HTML to render the
article views.

00:22:58.300 --> 00:22:59.950
And it actually works
really well in

00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:01.480
those particular cases.

00:23:01.480 --> 00:23:04.090
We're really saying, don't just
throw a WebView into the

00:23:04.090 --> 00:23:06.200
entire application, and make
it take over the sort of

00:23:06.200 --> 00:23:09.130
standard core UI elements.

00:23:09.130 --> 00:23:11.650
ROMAN NURIK: One last point I
wanted to make about web apps

00:23:11.650 --> 00:23:13.260
versus native apps is.

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:16.000
There's a tendency for brands
to be like, oh we need to be

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:17.080
on Android, right?

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:18.340
And you mentioned this.

00:23:18.340 --> 00:23:19.670
And we need to be on android,
so we need to

00:23:19.670 --> 00:23:20.510
make a native app.

00:23:20.510 --> 00:23:24.970
But a ton of Android usage,
that's regular users, most of

00:23:24.970 --> 00:23:27.170
them use the browser
quite a bit.

00:23:27.170 --> 00:23:29.790
So that you're not losing
those users.

00:23:29.790 --> 00:23:32.230
They're going to access
your experience

00:23:32.230 --> 00:23:34.420
through a different mechanism.

00:23:34.420 --> 00:23:37.770
And if you think that a web
based solution is the best

00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:41.220
option, then that's going to
work for a lot of users.

00:23:41.220 --> 00:23:44.540
So don't immediately jump into,
oh, we need to just have

00:23:44.540 --> 00:23:48.390
this hybrid thing, where we just
throw our entire web app

00:23:48.390 --> 00:23:50.920
into a native APK So that
just doesn't work.

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:52.720
ADAM KOCH: Yeah, and I think
you'll find, if you do go and

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:54.540
throw a web view in, make
it take over the entire

00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:57.290
application, you're going to
violate a lot of these other

00:23:57.290 --> 00:23:58.950
things that we've talked
about today.

00:23:58.950 --> 00:24:02.370
Like the touch feedback, the
touch size, the UI elements,

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:03.080
the living in the past.

00:24:03.080 --> 00:24:05.410
All these things are very hard
to do if you're going to use a

00:24:05.410 --> 00:24:08.480
WebView to take over your
entire application.

00:24:08.480 --> 00:24:09.130
Moving on?

00:24:09.130 --> 00:24:11.400
ROMAN NURIK: Yep, moving on.

00:24:11.400 --> 00:24:12.270
Nick, you want to talk
about onboarding?

00:24:12.270 --> 00:24:15.560
NICK BUTCHER: [INAUDIBLE] we
have poor onboarding UX.

00:24:15.560 --> 00:24:18.920
So this is one of my
personal bugbears.

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:22.470
When you fire up an application
and 101 different

00:24:22.470 --> 00:24:25.550
things are competing for your
attention at the same time.

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:28.320
And none of them are what I look
at your app for, which is

00:24:28.320 --> 00:24:30.180
probably to see the content.

00:24:30.180 --> 00:24:32.400
This is a personal frustration
of mine.

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:36.450
So there's many things that
people tend to throw in

00:24:36.450 --> 00:24:37.300
at the first run.

00:24:37.300 --> 00:24:40.600
So things like requiring
registration straight away, a

00:24:40.600 --> 00:24:46.230
splash screen, popping up in
their own login provider, and

00:24:46.230 --> 00:24:47.060
so on, and so forth.

00:24:47.060 --> 00:24:50.380
And all of these things just
road bumps, or speed bumps,

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:52.790
stopping me from doing what
launched the app to do, which

00:24:52.790 --> 00:24:54.110
is see some content.

00:24:54.110 --> 00:24:57.890
So I would much rather see an
application that gets me to

00:24:57.890 --> 00:25:01.730
content as quickly as it can,
and then delays any necessary

00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:06.820
steps until they are
truly last minute.

00:25:06.820 --> 00:25:07.870
So log on, for example.

00:25:07.870 --> 00:25:10.550
Let me see some content, and
try and interact with it.

00:25:10.550 --> 00:25:12.560
And if I try to do an
interaction which requires log

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:13.820
on, then prompt for it.

00:25:13.820 --> 00:25:16.680
Because at that point, I can
understand exactly why you're

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:20.000
asking for this thing,
and so on.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:20.680
Splash screens.

00:25:20.680 --> 00:25:23.040
Another personal bugbear, it's
been in our design guidelines

00:25:23.040 --> 00:25:26.250
forever, that you shouldn't
really use splash screens.

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:28.290
They don't really serve much
purpose, other than Delaying

00:25:28.290 --> 00:25:30.940
you from getting to content
you want to see.

00:25:30.940 --> 00:25:34.250
So if you think that it's the
only way to embed branding

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:35.410
into your application,
then I think

00:25:35.410 --> 00:25:36.410
you have bigger problems.

00:25:36.410 --> 00:25:39.480
There really are much better
ways to provide branding to

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:40.070
your application.

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:43.260
Like using the action bar, and
your palette, and so forth.

00:25:43.260 --> 00:25:47.480
So I don't accept that
as an argument.

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:50.130
And then conversely, there's
lots of things you can use to

00:25:50.130 --> 00:25:52.550
actually easy onboarding
process.

00:25:52.550 --> 00:25:56.770
So for example, integrating with
popular log on providers.

00:25:56.770 --> 00:26:00.660
So things like Facebook,
Twitter, Google+ have

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:05.020
excellent single click
sign on providers.

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:07.040
You can even do intelligent
things.

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:08.370
Like use the package manager.

00:26:08.370 --> 00:26:11.080
Like a system component on
Android to detect of the user

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:13.460
has one of these native
applications installed, which

00:26:13.460 --> 00:26:16.940
is a pretty strong indicator
that they-- a user of one of

00:26:16.940 --> 00:26:19.540
these log on providing
services.

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:22.350
- And use that to
show or hide, or

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.060
reorder your log on options.

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:25.720
And they'll provide
a much slicker UX.

00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:28.140
If you really, really must force
someone to log in, with

00:26:28.140 --> 00:26:30.850
a username or password, for
example, then there's some

00:26:30.850 --> 00:26:31.650
clever stuff you can do.

00:26:31.650 --> 00:26:34.480
Like my phone already knows a
bunch of my email address or

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:37.340
usernames that were just
saved in the system.

00:26:37.340 --> 00:26:39.200
You can query for these and use
them all to complete, or

00:26:39.200 --> 00:26:40.650
pre-populate fields.

00:26:40.650 --> 00:26:42.860
You can query the system
to the users.

00:26:42.860 --> 00:26:45.646
Full name, and telephone
number, and

00:26:45.646 --> 00:26:46.330
so on, and so forth.

00:26:46.330 --> 00:26:49.940
So you can pre-fill a bunch
of different addresses.

00:26:49.940 --> 00:26:51.920
I've even seen applications
going a step further.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:55.940
If you really have to sign up
on the phone, do you really

00:26:55.940 --> 00:26:59.020
want to have to sit there
and peck out a password?

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:02.270
Why not offer to auto-generate
some random string.

00:27:02.270 --> 00:27:05.327
And let them hit Refresh
to rotate it

00:27:05.327 --> 00:27:06.180
to something different.

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:08.320
Because the user can always just
recess it later, as long

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:09.870
as they have their
email address.

00:27:09.870 --> 00:27:11.220
ROMAN NURIK: And they're
probably not going to remember

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:12.290
their password anyway.

00:27:12.290 --> 00:27:13.890
It's like, I oh, I just want
to put in some password and

00:27:13.890 --> 00:27:16.100
get past this screen.

00:27:16.100 --> 00:27:16.640
NICK BUTCHER: Exactly.

00:27:16.640 --> 00:27:21.000
So basically, do everything you
can to simplify the first

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:21.890
user experience, and get you to

00:27:21.890 --> 00:27:23.550
content as soon as possible.

00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:25.865
I think too often when we're
like designing and developing

00:27:25.865 --> 00:27:27.100
apps, you've looked
at the application

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:28.640
so many times, right?

00:27:28.640 --> 00:27:30.510
That you can see through
that process.

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:32.010
Or you logged in
the first time.

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:33.960
And after that, you then
continue to look at the

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:34.670
substance screens.

00:27:34.670 --> 00:27:37.550
Don't you about the first
impression that you're making

00:27:37.550 --> 00:27:38.760
on your users.

00:27:38.760 --> 00:27:40.660
So super important.

00:27:40.660 --> 00:27:42.970
I mean, this becomes even more
important if you're lucky

00:27:42.970 --> 00:27:46.570
enough to become featured,
or picked by a blog, or

00:27:46.570 --> 00:27:47.430
something like that.

00:27:47.430 --> 00:27:49.840
You'd be surprised at how many
users will install your

00:27:49.840 --> 00:27:51.940
application without fully
understanding the value

00:27:51.940 --> 00:27:52.830
proposition exactly.

00:27:52.830 --> 00:27:55.210
Understanding what it does,
just to try it out.

00:27:55.210 --> 00:27:57.430
And it the first thing you see
is a bunch of overlays

00:27:57.430 --> 00:27:59.400
explaining how to do stuff.

00:27:59.400 --> 00:28:01.150
And logins and pop-ups.

00:28:01.150 --> 00:28:03.285
They're forcing you to take more
steps before you get to

00:28:03.285 --> 00:28:05.510
the actual content, to show
them the actual value.

00:28:05.510 --> 00:28:07.760
Then, you'll have
a huge fall off.

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:10.970
ROMAN NURIK: On the converse,
completely on the opposite end

00:28:10.970 --> 00:28:15.220
of spectrum, if I open up your
app and I see an immediate

00:28:15.220 --> 00:28:18.450
empty list of you with
nothing there.

00:28:18.450 --> 00:28:21.260
Just like a little plus button
on the top right, and really

00:28:21.260 --> 00:28:22.700
just an empty screen.

00:28:22.700 --> 00:28:24.690
That is also poor communication
of the value

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:25.660
proposition.

00:28:25.660 --> 00:28:28.390
So empty states, which we'll
talk about very briefly.

00:28:28.390 --> 00:28:31.510
Empty states for collections are
actually a really valuable

00:28:31.510 --> 00:28:34.492
way of communicating that.

00:28:34.492 --> 00:28:34.990
All right.

00:28:34.990 --> 00:28:35.390
Moving on?

00:28:35.390 --> 00:28:37.120
I think we're running
low on time.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:39.505
The last one, number one.

00:28:39.505 --> 00:28:41.150
We should have done a drum roll,
but I guess we didn't

00:28:41.150 --> 00:28:42.700
have the time.

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:45.870
Android is not just phones
in portrait.

00:28:45.870 --> 00:28:49.120
What this means is, if you're
developing an app and you have

00:28:49.120 --> 00:28:52.590
a phone UI, don't lock
it into portrait.

00:28:52.590 --> 00:28:54.640
Make sure that the user
can rotate into

00:28:54.640 --> 00:28:56.380
landscape quite a few--

00:28:56.380 --> 00:28:58.290
I think something that
chopped up here.

00:28:58.290 --> 00:29:01.070
There's supposed to be a graphic
here, but whatever.

00:29:01.070 --> 00:29:05.430
Quite a few users actually
use phones in portrait--

00:29:05.430 --> 00:29:06.560
in landscape, rather.

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:10.320
Especially those with
maybe car docs, or

00:29:10.320 --> 00:29:13.320
even desktop docs.

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:16.660
So for example, if you're a
sports app, there should be a

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:18.570
landscape dashboard view,
or something.

00:29:18.570 --> 00:29:22.050
Especially if I'm in a car,
in some sort of doc.

00:29:22.050 --> 00:29:26.480
If you're another type of app,
or you're a news app or

00:29:26.480 --> 00:29:28.980
something, consider--

00:29:28.980 --> 00:29:31.150
think about how you
can rearrange your

00:29:31.150 --> 00:29:32.480
text so that it works.

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:34.750
And potentially even, switch
around your interactions.

00:29:34.750 --> 00:29:37.090
Maybe horizontal goes to
vertical swipe, or

00:29:37.090 --> 00:29:37.830
something like that.

00:29:37.830 --> 00:29:38.890
I'm not really sure.

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:43.310
But the point here is, don't
force your users to hold their

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:44.620
device in a certain way.

00:29:44.620 --> 00:29:47.710
And then another component of
this is that Android is not

00:29:47.710 --> 00:29:48.430
only phones.

00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:50.700
Android involves tablets
as well.

00:29:50.700 --> 00:29:53.090
And the line between tabled and
phone is kind of blurry.

00:29:53.090 --> 00:29:57.920
But really, Android
is really just--

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:00.680
well, I guess one of the ways
you can describe most Android

00:30:00.680 --> 00:30:03.710
devices right now is touch
screens ranging from about

00:30:03.710 --> 00:30:05.730
three inches to about
10 inches.

00:30:05.730 --> 00:30:08.000
So responsive design is
really important here.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.580
Make sure that your
app can respond to

00:30:10.580 --> 00:30:11.960
the size of the screen.

00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:14.740
And that it make best use of
white space, and best use of

00:30:14.740 --> 00:30:17.680
content in all those different
configurations.

00:30:17.680 --> 00:30:20.110
Not only that, Android
is also--

00:30:20.110 --> 00:30:21.520
it's not only about touch.

00:30:21.520 --> 00:30:26.400
There are some devices that are
D-pad focus at Google TV.

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:29.080
So definitely think about ways
in which you can response to

00:30:29.080 --> 00:30:32.710
your device in both portrait,
landscape, tablet, phone, and

00:30:32.710 --> 00:30:34.292
different input types.

00:30:34.292 --> 00:30:35.730
NICK BUTCHER: I think it's
really important the point

00:30:35.730 --> 00:30:37.340
you've thought about here
in this subtext.

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:40.270
That it sounds scary as well
saying being responsive to all

00:30:40.270 --> 00:30:42.200
these different form factors,
and so forth.

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:45.610
But there really is so much you
can do very, very easily.

00:30:45.610 --> 00:30:48.550
Things like upping the font
size when you have over a

00:30:48.550 --> 00:30:49.780
certain amount of space.

00:30:49.780 --> 00:30:50.895
Or changing the padding.

00:30:50.895 --> 00:30:53.970
Or going to a centered margin.

00:30:53.970 --> 00:30:57.420
Things like that can be
an hour of work, or

00:30:57.420 --> 00:30:58.490
two hours of work.

00:30:58.490 --> 00:31:00.850
And make your application
vastly

00:31:00.850 --> 00:31:02.390
better on a larger device.

00:31:02.390 --> 00:31:05.240
So it really is worth just
trying it out on a range of

00:31:05.240 --> 00:31:08.300
devices or emulators and
seeing how it goes.

00:31:08.300 --> 00:31:09.250
ROMAN NURIK: All right.

00:31:09.250 --> 00:31:11.760
With that, let's jump into some
quick honorable mentions

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:13.550
since we're running
super low on time.

00:31:13.550 --> 00:31:17.500
First, per the guidelines for
launcher icons, your app icon

00:31:17.500 --> 00:31:19.460
should really be a distinct
silhouette.

00:31:19.460 --> 00:31:23.440
I know there are a couple of
Google apps that don't really

00:31:23.440 --> 00:31:24.390
adhere to this guideline.

00:31:24.390 --> 00:31:25.380
But that's definitely
something that

00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:27.420
we're looking into.

00:31:27.420 --> 00:31:29.010
Don't forget, like I mentioned,
don't forget the

00:31:29.010 --> 00:31:30.710
empty states for your
collections.

00:31:30.710 --> 00:31:33.490
So if you have nothing in a
list, if you have, let's say,

00:31:33.490 --> 00:31:35.030
a to-do list.

00:31:35.030 --> 00:31:36.640
And if you have nothing in
there, if you have no to-do

00:31:36.640 --> 00:31:40.190
items, offer the user some ways
to add something to do,

00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:41.340
maybe like a Plus button.

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:45.470
Or introduce what is going
to happen once you

00:31:45.470 --> 00:31:47.010
press the Plus button.

00:31:47.010 --> 00:31:49.050
NICK BUTCHER: Or you have some
sample content in there.

00:31:49.050 --> 00:31:52.790
Like the to-do list might have
some sample to-do items.

00:31:52.790 --> 00:31:54.430
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, some sample
to-do items, like milk,

00:31:54.430 --> 00:31:56.450
cheese, eggs, and so on.

00:31:56.450 --> 00:31:57.970
Graphic assets should
be crisp.

00:31:57.970 --> 00:31:59.780
I think most folks are starting
to his correctly.

00:31:59.780 --> 00:32:03.510
But definitely make sure
to provide XHDPI.

00:32:03.510 --> 00:32:08.220
And now with Samsung Galaxy
S4, HTC1, XXHTPIS.

00:32:08.220 --> 00:32:10.900
Those are becoming the norm.

00:32:10.900 --> 00:32:12.480
Take advantage of platform
features.

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:16.200
Make sure that especially if
you're in a category that is

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:18.890
heavy on widgets, like sports,
or news, make sure

00:32:18.890 --> 00:32:20.440
to provide a widget.

00:32:20.440 --> 00:32:23.440
And then make sure to provide
expendable notifications.

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:25.160
It's too easy, it's so, so.

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:26.110
NICK BUTCHER: I have to run.

00:32:26.110 --> 00:32:27.480
ROMAN NURIK: Say what?

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:28.060
NICK BUTCHER: I have to go.

00:32:28.060 --> 00:32:28.830
I'm getting kicked
out of my room.

00:32:28.830 --> 00:32:29.250
ROMAN NURIK: Oh, OK.

00:32:29.250 --> 00:32:32.560
All right, see you, Nick.

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:35.560
So make sure to provide
expandable notifications.

00:32:35.560 --> 00:32:38.600
They're just so easy to add.

00:32:38.600 --> 00:32:40.390
Lastly, notifications.

00:32:40.390 --> 00:32:41.660
You should use them correctly.

00:32:41.660 --> 00:32:43.900
Don't show too many
notifications.

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:45.490
Show them in appropriate
fashion.

00:32:45.490 --> 00:32:47.540
Show them an appropriate time.

00:32:47.540 --> 00:32:49.660
And then for the icons
themselves, the notification

00:32:49.660 --> 00:32:53.890
icons in the status bar, make
sure to use white icons.

00:32:53.890 --> 00:32:54.750
Don't add any color.

